The '''American Osteopathic Boards of Ophthalmology and Otolaryngology - Head and Neck Surgery (AOBOO)''' is a joint organization that provides [[board certification]] to qualified [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|Doctors of Osteopathic Medicine]] (D.O.) who specialize in the medical and surgical treatment of the eye ([[Ophthalmology|ophthalmologists]]) and to qualified Doctors of Osteopathic Medicine who specialize in the medical and surgical treatment of the ears, nose, and throat ([[Otolaryngology|otolaryngologists]]). The boards belong to the 18 [[Specialty (medicine)|medical specialty]] certifying boards approved by the [[American Osteopathic Association Bureau of Osteopathic Specialists]] of the [[American Osteopathic Association]].<ref>{{cite web|title=AOA Specialty Certifying Boards|url=https://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/development/aoa-board-certification/Pages/aoa-specialty-boards.aspx|publisher=American Osteopathic Association|accessdate=14 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=AOA Boards of Ophthalmology and Otolaryngologyl
 |url= http://www.hwic.org/experts/details.php?id=3120|year=2011|publisher=Health Workforce Information Center|accessdate=14 September 2012}}</ref> As of December 2011, 736 osteopathic ophthalmologists and otolaryngologists held active certification with the AOBOO.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ayres|first=Ronald E|coauthors=S Scheinthal, C Gross, and E Bell.|title=Changes to Osteopathic Specialty Board Certification|journal=Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|year=2012|month=April|volume=112|issue=4|pages=226–231|url=http://www.jaoa.org/content/112/4/226.full.pdf+html|accessdate=14 September 2012}}</ref>
==Board certification==
Initial board certification is available to eligible [[Osteopathic medicine in the United States|osteopathic]] ophthalmologists and otolaryngologists who have successfully completed an American Osteopathic Association-approved [[medical residency|residency]] in ophthalmology, otolaryngology, or otolaryngology/facial plastic surgery, two years of practice, and successful completion of written and oral exams. Board certified osteopathic ophthalmologists and otolaryngologists must renew their certification every ten years to avoid expiration of their board certification status.<ref name="castle">{{cite web |url=http://www.castleconnolly.com/resources/osteopathic.cfm|title=Medical Boards: Osteopathic |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=Castle Connolly Medical Ltd. |accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref><ref name= "requirements">{{cite web |url=http://www.aoboo.org/protocol-for-certification#content_top |title=Protocol for Certification |author= |year=2011 |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Boards of Ophthalmology and Otolaryngology |accessdate=14 September 2012 }}</ref> The American Osteopathic Boards of Ophthalmology and Otolaryngology offer voluntary recertification and upon passage of the required examinations grants board-certified status for a period of ten years.<ref name="requirements"/>

Board certification through the AOBOO is required of all ophthalmology and otolaryngology residency program directors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Basic Standards for Residency Training in Ophthalmology|url=http://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/Education/postdoctoral-training/Documents/basic-standards-ophthalmology-eff-7-12.pdf|publisher=American Osteopathic Association|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> 

Osteopathic ophthalmologists and otolaryngologists may also receive Certification of Added Qualifications (CAQ) in [[Otolaryngic allergy]] and in [[Sleep Medicine]].<ref name="castle"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Specialties & Subspecialties|url=http://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/development/aoa-board-certification/Pages/specialty-subspecialty-certification.aspx|publisher=AOA|accessdate=14 September 2012}}</ref> Eligibility for a CAQ in sleep medicine requires a one year fellowship, or documentation of equivalent clinical experience and training.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eligibility Requirements|url=http://www.aocsm.org/Eligibility%20Requirements.html|publisher=The American Osteopathic Conjoint Committee of Sleep Medicine|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref>  The Certification of Added Qualifications must be maintained through the process of recertification every 10 years and requires candidates to pass both oral and written examinations.<ref name="requirements"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aoboo.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/2013-Sleep-Medicine-CAQ-Information-Application-and-Registration-Forms.pdf |title=Application Requirements BOS Conjoint Commitee Certifying Examination in Sleep Medicine |author= |year=2011 |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Boards of Ophthalmology and Otolaryngology |accessdate=14 September 2012 }}</ref>

